response.stringValue: Understanding insurance terminology is essential to empowering you to take control of your health

title.stringValue: Ready to go over basic insurance terms?

response.stringValue: Alright. That, I can do! Here are the top insurance definitions to help you understand your health insurance:

title.stringValue: Can I tell you about how to find out what a doctor visit, lab test or other healthcare service will cost before you get it?

response.stringValue: OK — the first thing you should do is look at your insurance document to see if your healthcare provider is in-network or out-of-network

title.stringValue: In-network providers are those that have an agreement with your health insurance. Most often, copayments and other costs are less expensive for in-network providers

response.stringValue: Out-of-network providers are those who have no agreement with your healthcare plan
Your costs will be higher to see a healthcare professional who is out-of-network

title.stringValue: Just because one of your doctor's is in-network doesn't mean others who work at the same hospital are too

response.stringValue: Once you establish if your healthcare provider is in-network or out-of-network, you should call and ask what the cost is for the doctor visit, lab test, or other healthcare service
Lastly, you should call your insurance company to see how cost-sharing works for the service you're getting
From that, you'll be able to identify what your out-of-pocket costs will be 👏

title.stringValue: Would you like to learn about any of these topics?

response.stringValue: There's often confusion around whether or not a referral is needed to see a specialist

title.stringValue: Ready for my words of advice?

response.stringValue: If you need to be under the care of an asthma or allergy specialist, it's best to talk to your primary care doctor about which options are nearby
It's possible that your health plan will require you to have a referral before you're able to see a specialist
To ensure there are no surprise costs, you should always check with your insurance company before you see a specialist to see whether a referral is required 😊

title.stringValue: There are some types of plans that almost always require referrals. Can I tell you about them?

response.stringValue: Some states offer a health maintenance organization (HMO), which most often requires you to get a referral
If your insurance requires a referral and you don't get one first, your insurance won't cover your visit to that specialist

title.stringValue: So, it's best to always check first

response.stringValue: You can call your insurance company to ask whether or not you need a referral

response.stringValue: Cost-sharing reductions are discounts that lower the amount you have to pay for deductibles, copayments, and coinsurance
These reductions exist to help people who have insurance through the Health Insurance Marketplace pay their out-of-pocket costs

title.stringValue: Do you want to know if you're eligible?

response.stringValue: When you fill out a Marketplace application, you'll find out right away if you qualify for extra savings
You're able to use a premium tax credit for a plan in any metal category. But, if you also qualify for extra savings, you'll only get them if you choose a Silver plan
